The killing of Charlie Kirk has triggered a fierce fight over free speech. Politicians and pundits are calling for laws against “hate speech,” threatening prosecutions, and urging employers to fire anyone celebrating his death. But is this really justice—or the destruction of the very liberty Kirk defended? From Trump’s defiance to Matt Walsh’s critique, the debate exposes a dangerous hypocrisy: weaponizing censorship in the name of honoring a man whose life’s work was built on open expression. At stake is more than politics—it’s whether America still believes in free speech as a principle, not a tool of power.

In this conversation with Nick Fuentes I push him on faith, politics, and the future of the West in light of Charlie Kirk’s assassination. We get into the rise of populism, social media’s role in chaos and censorship, Israel and tribalism, the call to Christian love versus nihilism, and whether unity is even possible in an age of collapse. From Greta Thunberg to Tommy Robinson, Augustine to the Arab Spring, we wrestle with power, truth, and what it means to live as Christians now.
title: Faith, Power & Chaos: My Conversation With Nick Fuentes  - SF636
